\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 Purpose and Scope
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
The Democracy Clock is a standing, longitudinal report designed to measure and document changes in the condition of democratic governance in the United States over time. It tracks both erosion and repair of democratic norms, institutions, and practices using a consistent, evidence-based framework.\
\
The purpose of the Democracy Clock is not to persuade, predict, or provoke. It exists to 
\f2\b make democratic change legible
\f1\b0 \'97particularly when that change is incremental, normalized, or obscured by political noise. Democracies rarely collapse in a single moment. They degrade, or recover, through the accumulation of decisions, precedents, and institutional shifts. The Democracy Clock is built to record that accumulation.\
\
The report is intended for use by journalists and producers seeking factual grounding; policy staff and institutional leaders monitoring governance risk; educators and researchers studying democratic systems; and citizens seeking explanation rather than commentary. It is published as a public record and updated on a fixed cadence.\
\
The Democracy Clock is not an opinion column, an electoral forecast, or a partisan advocacy document. It does not evaluate political actors based on ideology or popularity. It measures democratic condition as expressed through verifiable actions and institutional outcomes.\
