\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 Conceptual Framework: Time as Democratic Condition
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
The Democracy Clock uses time as a metaphor for democratic condition. 
\f2\b Noon
\f1\b0  represents a fully functioning democratic republic. 
\f2\b Midnight
\f1\b0  represents democratic collapse or the consolidation of authoritarian rule. Movement toward or away from midnight reflects structural change, not sentiment, polling, or rhetoric.\
\
This framing is deliberate. Democratic decline is rarely abrupt. It proceeds through cumulative and often legal actions: the normalization of emergency powers, the erosion of oversight, the politicization of courts, the weakening of electoral safeguards, or the degradation of information integrity. Time-based framing captures direction, momentum, and persistence in a way that isolated headlines cannot.\
\
The Clock is explicitly 
\f2\b bidirectional
\f1\b0 . Democratic repair\'97through institutional strengthening, restoration of norms, judicial independence, electoral protection, or reassertion of legislative authority\'97can and does move the clock away from midnight. The framework is designed to record recovery as rigorously as decline.\
